
(Here's a generic request for referencing this)

In your page "How to Find Security Holes", please add something like
the following to the end of it (in "Information of Interest..."):

  David A. Wheeler has developed a document for programmers titled
"Secure Programming for Linux HOWTO," which is now included in the
<A HREF="http://www.linuxdoc.org">Linux Documentation Project</A>.
You can get a copy of this document at
<A HREF="http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs">http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs</A>.


Bibliography Listing:

Wheeler, David A.
"Secure Programming for Linux HOWTO."
Linux Documentation Project.
<A HREF="http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs">http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs</A>.


Simple listing:

<A HREF="http://www.dwheeler.com/secure-programs">Secure Programming
for Linux HOWTO</A>.

This HOWTO by David A. Wheeler provides a set of design and implementation
guidelines for writing secure programs for Linux systems.
Such programs include application programs used as viewers of remote data,
CGI scripts, network servers, and setuid/setgid programs.
This HOWTO is part of the Linux Documentation Project.


